  "response": "```json\n{\n  \"theorem_title\": \"Itô's formula for a twice continuously differentiable function of Brownian motion\",\n  \"theorem_statement\": \"Let \\\\((B_t)_{t\\\\ge 0}\\\\) be a standard one-dimensional Brownian motion, let \\\\(T>0\\\\), and let \\\\(f:\\\\mathbb{R}\\\\to\\\\mathbb{R}\\\\) be a \\\\(C^2\\\\) function. Assume for simplicity that \\\\(f'\\\\) and \\\\(f''\\\\) are bounded and that \\\\(f''\\\\) is uniformly continuous on \\\\(\\\\mathbb{R}\\\\). Then for every \\\\(t\\\\in[0,T]\\\\),\\n\\\\[\\nf(B_t)\\n=\\nf(B_0)\\n+\\n\\\\int_0^t f'(B_s)\\\\,dB_s\\n+\\n\\\\frac12\\\\int_0^t f''(B_s)\\\\,ds.\\n\\\\]\",\n  \"root_node_id\": \"ito_formula\",\n  \"nodes\": [\n    {\n      \"id\": \"ito_formula\",\n      \"title\": \"Itô's formula\",\n      \"informal_statement\": \"Under the given assumptions on \\\\(f\\\\) and \\\\(B_t\\\\), \\\\(f(B_t) = f(B_0) + \\\\int_0^t f'(B_s)\\\\,dB_s + \\\\frac12\\\\int_0^t f''(B_s)\\\\,ds\\\\).\",\n      \"informal_proof_text\": \"Fix \\\\(t\\\\in[0,T]\\\\), and let \\\\(0=t_0<t_1<\\\\cdots<t_n=t\\\\) be a partition of \\\\([0,t]\\\\). Using the deterministic Taylor expansion identity, we can write the telescoping sum \\\\(f(B_t)-f(B_0)\\\\) as the sum of three terms: a first-order term, a second-order term, and a remainder \\\\(R_n\\\\).\\n\\nFirst term: The left-endpoint sums \\\\(\\\\sum_{k=0}^{n-1} f'(B_{t_k})\\\\,\\\\Delta B_k\\\\) converge in \\\\(L^2\\\\) (and along a subsequence almost surely) to the Itô integral \\\\(\\\\int_0^t f'(B_s)\\\\,dB_s\\\\).\\n\\nSecond term: We split \\\\(\\\\frac12 \\\\sum_{k=0}^{n-1} f''(B_{t_k})(\\\\Delta B_k)^2\\\\) into \\\\(\\\\frac12 \\\\sum_{k=0}^{n-1} f''(B_{t_k})\\\\,\\\\Delta t_k\\\\) and a cross term \\\\(M_n = \\\\sum_{k=0}^{n-1} f''(B_{t_k})\\\\bigl((\\\\Delta B_k)^2-\\\\Delta t_k\\\\bigr)\\\\). The first sum is a Riemann sum converging almost surely to \\\\(\\\\frac12\\\\int_0^t f''(B_s)\\\\,ds\\\\). For the cross term, since \\\\(\\\\mathbb E\\\\bigl[(\\\\Delta B_k)^2-\\\\Delta t_k \\\\mid \\\\mathcal F_{t_k}\\\\bigr]=0\\\\) and \\\\(f''\\\\) is bounded by \\\\(C\\\\), \\\\(\\\\mathbb E[M_n^2] \\\\le 2C^2 \\\\sum_{k=0}^{n-1} (\\\\Delta t_k)^2\\\\), which tends to \\\\(0\\\\) as the mesh goes to zero. Thus the cross term vanishes in \\\\(L^2\\\\).\\n\\nThird term: By the deterministic bound on the remainder \\\\(R_n\\\\), we have \\\\(|R_n| \\\\le \\\\frac12\\\\,\\\\omega\\\\!\\\\left(\\\\max_k |\\\\Delta B_k|\\\\right)\\\\sum_{k=0}^{n-1}(\\\\Delta B_k)^2\\\\). Since Brownian paths are almost surely uniformly continuous on \\\\([0,t]\\\\), \\\\(\\\\max_k |\\\\Delta B_k| \\\\to 0\\\\) almost surely. The quadratic variation \\\\(\\\\sum_{k=0}^{n-1}(\\\\Delta B_k)^2 \\\\to t\\\\) in probability. Thus \\\\(R_n \\\\to 0\\\\) in probability.\\n\\nCombining these limits as the mesh tends to zero yields Itô's formula.\"\n    },\n    {\n      \"id\": \"deterministic_taylor_expansion\",\n      \"title\": \"Deterministic Taylor Expansion and Remainder Bound\",\n      \"informal_statement\": \"Let \\\\(f\\\\) be a \\\\(C^2\\\\) function with uniformly continuous second derivative \\\\(f''\\\\), and let \\\\(\\\\omega(\\\\delta)\\\\) be a modulus of continuity for \\\\(f''\\\\). For any sequence \\\\(B_{t_0}, B_{t_1}, \\\\dots, B_{t_n}\\\\), let \\\\(\\\\Delta B_k := B_{t_{k+1}}-B_{t_k}\\\\). Then\\n\\\\[\\n\\\\sum_{k=0}^{n-1}\\\\bigl(f(B_{t_{k+1}})-f(B_{t_k})\\\\bigr)\\n=\\n\\\\sum_{k=0}^{n-1} f'(B_{t_k})\\\\,\\\\Delta B_k\\n+\\n\\\\frac12 \\\\sum_{k=0}^{n-1} f''(B_{t_k})(\\\\Delta B_k)^2\\n+\\nR_n,\\n\\\\]\\nwhere the remainder \\\\(R_n\\\\) satisfies\\n\\\\[\\n|R_n|\\n\\\\le\\n\\\\frac12\\\\,\\\\omega\\\\!\\\\left(\\\\max_k |\\\\Delta B_k|\\\\right)\\\\sum_{k=0}^{n-1}(\\\\Delta B_k)^2.\\n\\\\]\",\n      \"informal_proof_text\": \"We begin from the telescoping identity\\n\\\\[\\nf(B_{t_n})-f(B_{t_0})\\n=\\n\\\\sum_{k=0}^{n-1}\\\\bigl(f(B_{t_{k+1}})-f(B_{t_k})\\\\bigr).\\n\\\\]\\nNow apply Taylor's theorem with remainder to each increment. For each \\\\(k\\\\), there exists a point \\\\(\\\\xi_k\\\\) between \\\\(B_{t_k}\\\\) and \\\\(B_{t_{k+1}}\\\\) such that\\n\\\\[\\nf(B_{t_{k+1}})\\n=\\nf(B_{t_k})\\n+\\nf'(B_{t_k})\\\\,\\\\Delta B_k\\n+\\n\\\\frac12 f''(B_{t_k}) (\\\\Delta B_k)^2\\n+\\n\\\\frac12\\\\bigl(f''(\\\\xi_k)-f''(B_{t_k})\\\\bigr)(\\\\Delta B_k)^2.\\n\\\\]\\nSumming over \\\\(k\\\\) gives the stated identity with\\n\\\\[\\nR_n\\n:=\\n\\\\frac12\\\\sum_{k=0}^{n-1}\\\\bigl(f''(\\\\xi_k)-f''(B_{t_k})\\\\bigr)(\\\\Delta B_k)^2.\\n\\\\]\\nSince \\\\(\\\\xi_k\\\\) lies between \\\\(B_{t_k}\\\\) and \\\\(B_{t_{k+1}}\\\\), \\\\(|\\\\xi_k - B_{t_k}| \\\\le |\\\\Delta B_k|\\\\). Because \\\\(\\\\omega\\\\) is a modulus of continuity for \\\\(f''\\\\),\\n\\\\[\\n|f''(\\\\xi_k)-f''(B_{t_k})|\\n\\\\le\\n\\\\omega(|\\\\Delta B_k|).\\n\\\\]\\nTherefore,\\n\\\\[\\n|R_n|\\n\\\\le\\n\\\\frac12 \\\\sum_{k=0}^{n-1}\\\\omega(|\\\\Delta B_k|)(\\\\Delta B_k)^2\\n\\\\le\\n\\\\frac12\\\\,\\\\omega\\\\!\\\\left(\\\\max_k |\\\\Delta B_k|\\\\right)\\\\sum_{k=0}^{n-1}(\\\\Delta B_k)^2.\\n\\\\]\"\n    }\n  ],\n  \"edges\": [\n    {\n      \"source_id\": \"deterministic_taylor_expansion\",\n      \"target_id\": \"ito_formula\",\n      \"label\": \"provides the algebraic expansion and remainder bound\",\n      \"explanation\": \"The deterministic Taylor expansion decomposes the telescoping sum into the discrete Itô integral, the quadratic variation term, and a bounded remainder, which are then analyzed stochastically to prove the main theorem.\"\n    }\n  ],\n  \"candidates\": [\n    {\n      \"node_id\": \"deterministic_taylor_expansion\",\n      \"priority\": \"high\",\n      \"rationale\": \"This lemma is a purely deterministic, algebraic, and analytic identity combined with an inequality. It completely isolates the Taylor expansion and the modulus-of-continuity bound on the remainder from the complexities of stochastic processes. This makes it an ideal, formalization-sensitive 'formal island' that ca